1
00:00:03,291 --> 00:00:04,791
TAKESHI: Heroes are powerful.

2
00:00:06,250 --> 00:00:08,125
They fight the good fight alone.

3
00:00:10,666 --> 00:00:11,583
And when they're done,

4
00:00:11,666 --> 00:00:14,541
they melt back into the night.

5
00:00:18,666 --> 00:00:21,125
Kind of like he did.

6
00:00:22,666 --> 00:00:24,750
[scattered applause]

7
00:00:25,666 --> 00:00:27,541
<i>Exactly like he did.</i>

8
00:00:28,666 --> 00:00:30,208
- [panting]

9
00:00:32,166 --> 00:00:33,416
- That was good, right?

10
00:00:33,500 --> 00:00:35,166
- He was disqualified
the moment he stopped, though.

11
00:00:39,333 --> 00:00:40,708
-<i> There's scattered applause.</i>

12
00:00:40,791 --> 00:00:42,625
<i>They're confused.</i>

13
00:00:42,708 --> 00:00:44,791
<i>Not that it matters.</i>

14
00:00:44,875 --> 00:00:47,583
<i>I played for the sake</i>
<i>of one person.</i>

15
00:00:47,666 --> 00:00:49,583
<i>Did it reach her?</i>

16
00:00:53,791 --> 00:00:55,958
<i>I hope that it did.</i>

17
00:00:56,041 --> 00:00:58,125
["Hikaru Nara" playing]

18
00:00:58,208 --> 00:01:04,250
♪♪

19
00:01:04,333 --> 00:01:10,291
♪♪

20
00:01:10,375 --> 00:01:12,291
[singing in Japanese]

21
00:01:12,375 --> 00:01:20,500
♪♪

22
00:01:20,583 --> 00:01:30,500
♪♪

23
00:01:30,583 --> 00:01:39,708
♪♪

24
00:01:39,791 --> 00:01:48,958
♪♪

25
00:01:49,041 --> 00:01:58,166
♪♪

26
00:01:58,250 --> 00:02:07,375
♪♪

27
00:02:07,458 --> 00:02:15,583
♪♪

28
00:02:15,666 --> 00:02:24,791
♪♪

29
00:02:24,875 --> 00:02:28,125
[scattered applause]

30
00:02:29,666 --> 00:02:31,583
[Emi grunts]

31
00:02:39,041 --> 00:02:40,083
- Hmm?

32
00:02:44,125 --> 00:02:45,250
- Listen up, you.
- [gasps]

33
00:02:45,333 --> 00:02:49,500
- This competition is a place
to show your very best.

34
00:02:49,583 --> 00:02:50,583
It is not a place

35
00:02:50,666 --> 00:02:52,833
for working out your issues
in public.

36
00:03:01,041 --> 00:03:04,208
- Still the same
prickly old geezer. Am I right?

37
00:03:04,291 --> 00:03:07,250
The stick up his butt
gets worse every year.

38
00:03:07,333 --> 00:03:09,083
God help us.

39
00:03:09,166 --> 00:03:10,583
Hey, Mr. Quitter.

40
00:03:10,666 --> 00:03:11,583
- Ms. Seto?

41
00:03:11,666 --> 00:03:14,041
- I'm practically family,
you butt-head.

42
00:03:14,125 --> 00:03:16,291
- I totally meant
to say, "Hiroko"!

43
00:03:17,416 --> 00:03:19,083
I guess you got a haircut.

44
00:03:19,166 --> 00:03:20,083
Took me a second
to recognize you.

45
00:03:20,166 --> 00:03:22,750
- Women change their hair
all the time,

46
00:03:22,833 --> 00:03:25,750
not like guys,
with their one look.

47
00:03:25,833 --> 00:03:28,291
After all, it's been two years.

48
00:03:30,833 --> 00:03:31,875
[chuckles]

49
00:03:33,208 --> 00:03:34,250
- That chick's
a stone-cold fox.

50
00:03:34,333 --> 00:03:36,791
- It feels like I've
seen her somewhere before.

51
00:03:36,875 --> 00:03:39,166
- Real nice, Kousei,

52
00:03:39,250 --> 00:03:40,875
keeping that chick a secret.

53
00:03:40,958 --> 00:03:42,791
I thought we were bros,
you monster.

54
00:03:42,875 --> 00:03:44,458
- Oh, she's the one

55
00:03:44,541 --> 00:03:46,791
who always visited
Kousei's mom back in the day.

56
00:03:46,875 --> 00:03:48,916
- That's Hiroko Seto.

57
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:50,958
She's Japan's leading pianist.

58
00:03:51,041 --> 00:03:52,333
- Hey, Koharu.
It's been a long time.

59
00:03:52,416 --> 00:03:53,958
TSUBAKI: It makes sense
she would be there.

60
00:03:54,041 --> 00:03:55,166
Kousei's mom and she
were classmates in college.

61
00:03:55,250 --> 00:03:58,875
- I guess the friendship lasted.
- [laughs]

62
00:03:58,958 --> 00:04:01,625
<i>- Weird, huh? There's stuff</i>
<i>about Kousei's life</i>

63
00:04:01,708 --> 00:04:02,833
<i>I know nothing about.</i>

64
00:04:03,750 --> 00:04:05,625
- Huh?!
- Whoa!

65
00:04:05,708 --> 00:04:06,875
- [squeals]

66
00:04:06,958 --> 00:04:07,958
- I, uh--

67
00:04:08,041 --> 00:04:10,166
Everybody's staring
at us, Hiroko.

68
00:04:12,250 --> 00:04:13,791
SAKI:<i> Hey, Hiroko,</i>
<i>do you want to hold him?</i>

69
00:04:13,875 --> 00:04:16,166
- Uh, I'll give it a try.

70
00:04:16,250 --> 00:04:17,708
- Make sure
you support his head.

71
00:04:17,791 --> 00:04:20,000
Gently now.

72
00:04:20,083 --> 00:04:21,625
- [chuckles]

73
00:04:21,708 --> 00:04:23,541
- Isn't he adorable?

74
00:04:23,625 --> 00:04:24,708
We decided to name him Kousei.

75
00:04:24,791 --> 00:04:26,166
- Future pianist?

76
00:04:26,250 --> 00:04:29,583
- Not if I have anything
to say about it.

77
00:04:29,666 --> 00:04:31,583
That's a tough life for a kid.

78
00:04:33,875 --> 00:04:36,000
<i>- Now you gotta</i>
<i>turn him into a pianist.</i>

79
00:04:36,083 --> 00:04:36,875
<i>- I don't know.</i>
<i>- Oh, look at him!</i>

80
00:04:36,958 --> 00:04:39,166
<i>The kid's a natural.</i>

81
00:04:39,250 --> 00:04:41,083
KOUSEI:<i> Help me.</i>

82
00:04:41,166 --> 00:04:41,833
[crying]<i> Help me.</i>

83
00:04:41,916 --> 00:04:44,666
HIROKO:<i> I'm sorry, Kousei.</i>

84
00:04:44,750 --> 00:04:46,000
-<i> Mom.</i>

85
00:04:46,083 --> 00:04:49,208
-<i> Please forgive me.</i>

86
00:04:51,458 --> 00:04:54,916
Who told you you could grow up,
you butt-head?

87
00:04:56,166 --> 00:04:57,291
- You smell like an ashtray.

88
00:04:59,250 --> 00:05:00,375
- Hey, now.

89
00:05:00,458 --> 00:05:02,541
At least I don't smell
like a teenage boy.

90
00:05:02,625 --> 00:05:03,541
[laughs] Your friends over there

91
00:05:03,625 --> 00:05:05,666
look like they're
gonna burst a gasket.

92
00:05:05,750 --> 00:05:07,041
- Uh...

93
00:05:07,125 --> 00:05:09,208
- [yelps]
- [all gasp] We're busted!

94
00:05:09,291 --> 00:05:11,041
- You're staying
for the results, right?

95
00:05:11,125 --> 00:05:12,833
- Huh? Nah.

96
00:05:12,916 --> 00:05:14,666
I don't care about my score,

97
00:05:14,750 --> 00:05:16,875
and I'm out of the running,
anyway.

98
00:05:16,958 --> 00:05:18,541
- [chuckles]

99
00:05:18,625 --> 00:05:20,541
- Yeah! When you bomb
at a competition,

100
00:05:20,625 --> 00:05:21,583
you don't half-ass it!

101
00:05:21,666 --> 00:05:23,208
- Way to be supportive!

102
00:05:23,291 --> 00:05:24,625
- Either way,

103
00:05:24,708 --> 00:05:26,625
you should be there
when the results go up.

104
00:05:26,708 --> 00:05:28,500
It's competition etiquette.

105
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:30,916
- [yelps]
- So which one of 'em is it,

106
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:33,833
huh? Long-haired chick?

107
00:05:33,916 --> 00:05:35,875
Short-haired chick? 'Fess up.

108
00:05:35,958 --> 00:05:37,916
I know you're in love
with one of 'em.

109
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:39,083
- Where do you get this stuff?

110
00:05:39,166 --> 00:05:40,250
- Say what you want.

111
00:05:40,333 --> 00:05:41,750
I ain't buyin' it.

112
00:05:42,500 --> 00:05:45,083
Your playing told me as much.

113
00:05:45,166 --> 00:05:47,500
It sang out the words,
"I love you."

114
00:05:48,666 --> 00:05:49,833
Didn't you know?

115
00:05:49,916 --> 00:05:51,166
Or maybe you're
pretending not to.

116
00:05:51,250 --> 00:05:54,041
Emotions can be funny things.

117
00:05:54,125 --> 00:05:55,750
They sneak up on you.

118
00:05:55,833 --> 00:05:56,833
When you're young,

119
00:05:56,916 --> 00:06:00,041
the piano turns your heart
into an open book.

120
00:06:00,125 --> 00:06:01,833
Brace yourself.

121
00:06:01,916 --> 00:06:03,666
Don't be a stranger, yeah?

122
00:06:05,791 --> 00:06:07,291
-<i> It's not like that.</i>

123
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:12,000
<i>What I'm feeling is gratitude.</i>

124
00:06:13,166 --> 00:06:15,083
<i>After all, she's...</i>

125
00:06:16,333 --> 00:06:19,000
<i>she's the girl</i>
<i>who likes my best friend,</i>

126
00:06:19,083 --> 00:06:20,000
<i>and me...</i>

127
00:06:20,083 --> 00:06:22,166
<i>I'm just Friend A.</i>

128
00:06:22,250 --> 00:06:25,083
- [crowd murmuring]
- All right.

129
00:06:25,166 --> 00:06:27,541
We're about to post the results
of the first round.

130
00:06:31,041 --> 00:06:32,750
- Look! There's my name!

131
00:06:32,833 --> 00:06:34,750
- Cool.
- Is Arima on the list?

132
00:06:36,041 --> 00:06:38,750
<i>- Hard to imagine</i>
<i>Arima not making the cut.</i>

133
00:06:44,833 --> 00:06:47,041
- [sighs]

134
00:06:47,125 --> 00:06:49,791
<i>Heroes don't crumble.</i>

135
00:06:49,875 --> 00:06:51,500
<i>They suck it up and fight on.</i>

136
00:06:51,916 --> 00:06:53,541
- [gasps]

137
00:06:55,125 --> 00:06:56,000
-<i> It's no surprise.</i>

138
00:06:56,083 --> 00:06:58,750
<i>I did stop halfway.</i>

139
00:06:58,833 --> 00:06:59,666
- No way!
- [gasps]

140
00:06:59,750 --> 00:07:01,416
- I did it!
There's my name, see?

141
00:07:01,500 --> 00:07:04,416
- [sighs]
Guess I fell short again.

142
00:07:04,500 --> 00:07:06,750
- I'll practice even harder
for next year.

143
00:07:06,833 --> 00:07:07,833
- No more chances.

144
00:07:07,916 --> 00:07:09,750
- I hate this.

145
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,333
- All that work...

146
00:07:14,416 --> 00:07:15,500
what a waste.

147
00:07:21,125 --> 00:07:22,958
-<i> Takeshi.</i>

148
00:07:23,041 --> 00:07:25,500
- You played like a joke today.

149
00:07:25,583 --> 00:07:28,333
What the hell have you
been doing all this time?!

150
00:07:28,416 --> 00:07:32,000
<i>All I want to do</i>
<i>is defeat Arima.</i>

151
00:07:32,083 --> 00:07:35,333
You couldn't even get through
that song without stopping.

152
00:07:35,416 --> 00:07:36,541
Why did you even bother
with that train wreck?

153
00:07:37,583 --> 00:07:41,208
<i>What happened to the Arima</i>
<i>from my childhood,</i>

154
00:07:41,291 --> 00:07:43,541
<i>my invincible rival?</i>

155
00:07:43,625 --> 00:07:44,833
<i>Where did he go?</i>

156
00:07:45,708 --> 00:07:48,750
<i>My hero always carries the day.</i>

157
00:07:48,833 --> 00:07:50,166
<i>My hero's bulletproof.</i>

158
00:07:50,250 --> 00:07:52,833
<i>You knew the moment you stopped</i>

159
00:07:52,916 --> 00:07:56,583
<i>that they'd never bump you up</i>
<i>past prelims, so why?</i>

160
00:07:57,625 --> 00:08:01,041
<i>Why do you have</i>
<i>that look on your face?</i>

161
00:08:01,125 --> 00:08:02,041
<i>Heroes always win,</i>

162
00:08:02,125 --> 00:08:04,416
<i>no matter what.</i>

163
00:08:04,500 --> 00:08:06,208
<i>Watching you fail, it's like--</i>

164
00:08:06,291 --> 00:08:08,041
<i>you're just another person.</i>

165
00:08:11,333 --> 00:08:12,708
- Train wreck?

166
00:08:12,791 --> 00:08:14,750
Yeah, I assumed as much.

167
00:08:14,833 --> 00:08:17,833
But I'm not really
in a position to make that call.

168
00:08:17,916 --> 00:08:19,708
- [gasps]

169
00:08:19,791 --> 00:08:20,708
-<i> There's a rumor</i>

170
00:08:20,791 --> 00:08:23,416
<i>Arima can't even</i>
<i>hear the notes.</i>

171
00:08:23,500 --> 00:08:25,583
-<i> I guess it's true.</i>

172
00:08:25,666 --> 00:08:29,000
- I wasn't trying
to waste anybody's time.

173
00:08:29,083 --> 00:08:30,125
I practiced 'til I passed out.

174
00:08:30,208 --> 00:08:32,666
I gave it my all.

175
00:08:32,750 --> 00:08:35,333
-<i> You're you, no matter what.</i>

176
00:08:36,291 --> 00:08:37,250
- So if I turned in
a bad performance

177
00:08:37,333 --> 00:08:40,333
despite that, I guess...

178
00:08:41,250 --> 00:08:43,458
I guess that's who I am.

179
00:08:43,541 --> 00:08:46,041
Right now,
that's all I'm good for.

180
00:08:46,125 --> 00:08:47,375
- [gasps]

181
00:08:49,458 --> 00:08:52,833
- Mozart did say
we should go on a journey.

182
00:08:54,166 --> 00:08:56,208
<i>Where this journey</i>
<i>is going to take me,</i>

183
00:08:56,291 --> 00:08:58,083
<i>who can tell?</i>

184
00:08:58,166 --> 00:09:00,500
<i>But I've taken the first step.</i>

185
00:09:03,333 --> 00:09:05,041
I'm not alone, though.

186
00:09:05,125 --> 00:09:06,875
All of us are in this together.

187
00:09:15,791 --> 00:09:17,458
<i>That's right.</i>

188
00:09:17,541 --> 00:09:21,916
<i>I'm a musician,</i>
<i>just like you two.</i>

189
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:24,500
<i>That's why I'm moving on.</i>

190
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:28,875
[footsteps echoing]

191
00:09:33,083 --> 00:09:35,791
- [sighs] He's him,
but different.

192
00:09:35,875 --> 00:09:39,083
- I guess he finally found it,
a reason to play.

193
00:09:40,750 --> 00:09:42,458
-<i> During his song,</i>

194
00:09:42,541 --> 00:09:44,333
<i>just for a moment,</i>

195
00:09:44,416 --> 00:09:46,916
<i>it reminded me</i>
<i>of the boy he used to be.</i>

196
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:50,791
[dog barking]

197
00:09:51,750 --> 00:09:54,291
WATARI: Say something
to him, Tsubaki.

198
00:09:54,375 --> 00:09:55,625
He's all depressed and junk

199
00:09:55,708 --> 00:09:57,333
because he blew it today,
so step up.

200
00:09:57,416 --> 00:09:58,125
- Maybe it's a guy thing.

201
00:09:58,208 --> 00:10:00,416
You talk to him.

202
00:10:00,500 --> 00:10:03,625
- [both gasp]
- I'm fine, you guys, really.

203
00:10:03,708 --> 00:10:05,083
It doesn't bother me.

204
00:10:05,166 --> 00:10:07,583
- Well, then, we're good.

205
00:10:07,666 --> 00:10:10,000
[crossing bell ringing]

206
00:10:15,750 --> 00:10:19,000
<i>- This competition is a place</i>
<i>to show your very best,</i>

207
00:10:19,083 --> 00:10:21,541
<i>not working out</i>
<i>your issues in public.</i>

208
00:10:22,041 --> 00:10:23,833
[fist creaks]

209
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:27,208
-<i> You played like a joke today.</i>

210
00:10:27,291 --> 00:10:29,875
<i>What the hell have you</i>
<i>been doing all this time?!</i>

211
00:10:29,958 --> 00:10:30,791
-<i> Listen!</i>

212
00:10:32,708 --> 00:10:34,833
<i>- He's a robot.</i>
<i>- The Human Metronome.</i>

213
00:10:34,916 --> 00:10:38,208
<i>- Kid's nothing more</i>
<i>than his mother's puppet.</i>

214
00:10:38,291 --> 00:10:40,041
KOUSEI:<i> They think I'm a robot,</i>

215
00:10:40,125 --> 00:10:42,208
<i>but if I am, then...</i>

216
00:10:42,291 --> 00:10:44,458
-<i> I ruined it for everyone!</i>

217
00:10:44,541 --> 00:10:47,041
<i>- Well, that was</i>
<i>my chance at stardom.</i>

218
00:10:47,125 --> 00:10:49,125
[crossing bell ringing]

219
00:10:49,208 --> 00:10:51,333
- [gasps]

220
00:10:51,416 --> 00:10:52,458
- Hmm?
- Huh?

221
00:10:54,833 --> 00:10:55,541
TSUBAKI: Hey! Kousei!

222
00:10:55,625 --> 00:10:57,875
WATARI: Whoa! We got a live one!

223
00:10:57,958 --> 00:11:00,500
-<i> Why do I feel all this stuff?</i>

224
00:11:00,583 --> 00:11:02,166
<i>What got through my armor?</i>

225
00:11:03,875 --> 00:11:05,166
- KOUSEI:<i> Go.</i>
- [panting]

226
00:11:05,250 --> 00:11:05,916
-<i> Go!</i>

227
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:08,041
<i>Go!</i>

228
00:11:11,500 --> 00:11:13,416
[screaming]

229
00:11:13,500 --> 00:11:15,000
[train horn honks]

230
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:19,583
<i>I'm the same</i>
<i>as Watari and Tsubaki</i>

231
00:11:19,666 --> 00:11:21,166
-<i> and even you.</i>
- [screaming]

232
00:11:21,250 --> 00:11:22,250
<i>I'm a person inside!</i>

233
00:11:22,333 --> 00:11:24,958
[Watari laughs] He's nuts.

234
00:11:25,041 --> 00:11:26,500
TSUBAKI: Stop running!

235
00:11:26,583 --> 00:11:27,041
[entry bell rings]

236
00:11:27,125 --> 00:11:28,291
- Hey, I'm home.

237
00:11:28,375 --> 00:11:30,833
- You look pretty happy.

238
00:11:30,916 --> 00:11:32,333
I guess Arima did well, then.

239
00:11:32,416 --> 00:11:34,125
- Disqualified. And great!

240
00:11:34,208 --> 00:11:36,375
YOSHIYUKI: You know that
doesn't make sense, right?

241
00:11:36,458 --> 00:11:37,916
- I'll explain later.

242
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:38,916
RYOUKO: Guess what, honey.

243
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:39,416
A letter came for you.

244
00:11:39,500 --> 00:11:42,208
- Yeah? Curious.

245
00:11:42,291 --> 00:11:43,916
I'm gonna get changed.

246
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:45,041
I'm all sweaty
from running around.

247
00:11:45,125 --> 00:11:47,625
[pants]

248
00:11:52,375 --> 00:11:52,708
[bed creaks]

249
00:12:05,166 --> 00:12:08,208
[doorbell rings]

250
00:12:08,291 --> 00:12:10,083
- [insects buzzing]
- [phone line ringing]

251
00:12:10,166 --> 00:12:12,333
[doorbell rings]

252
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:16,458
- [gasps]

253
00:12:16,541 --> 00:12:18,250
[shoes scraping]

254
00:12:18,333 --> 00:12:19,291
[footsteps pattering]

255
00:12:19,375 --> 00:12:21,583
[Hiroko gasps]

256
00:12:22,541 --> 00:12:24,041
Oh, my God!

257
00:12:28,208 --> 00:12:29,333
Kousei!

258
00:12:29,416 --> 00:12:31,041
- [groans]
- Go for the head!

259
00:12:31,125 --> 00:12:32,208
He's a freaking zombie!

260
00:12:32,291 --> 00:12:33,833
- Where'd he go? Where'd he go?!

261
00:12:33,916 --> 00:12:36,041
- Oh, hey. Good morning.

262
00:12:36,125 --> 00:12:36,791
I'm glad to see you and all,

263
00:12:36,875 --> 00:12:39,708
but why are you in my house?

264
00:12:41,041 --> 00:12:42,375
- I'm here, 'cause somebody

265
00:12:42,458 --> 00:12:44,250
wouldn't pick up the phone,
even though I called,

266
00:12:44,333 --> 00:12:45,458
like, a billion times,
you punk!

267
00:12:45,541 --> 00:12:46,916
[Kousei screams]

268
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:49,416
- [growls]
You didn't even change

269
00:12:49,500 --> 00:12:51,041
out of your clothes,
you little slug.

270
00:12:51,125 --> 00:12:52,875
Get your ass
to the bath, already.

271
00:12:52,958 --> 00:12:54,333
You want me to give you one?

272
00:12:54,416 --> 00:12:55,375
- Whoa!
- It wouldn't be the first time.

273
00:12:55,458 --> 00:12:57,000
- [zipper unzips]
- No. I got it. I'm good.

274
00:12:57,083 --> 00:12:58,416
Thanks for the offer,
but I'm gonna pass.

275
00:12:58,500 --> 00:12:59,416
- [scoffs]

276
00:12:59,500 --> 00:13:01,375
<i>Nothing I haven't seen before.</i>

277
00:13:01,458 --> 00:13:02,541
[gasps]

278
00:13:05,166 --> 00:13:06,291
[chuckles]

279
00:13:10,541 --> 00:13:14,416
<i>Up all night playing the piano</i>
<i>'til he conked out.</i>

280
00:13:15,375 --> 00:13:16,958
KOUSEI:<i> Hiroko.</i>

281
00:13:18,333 --> 00:13:20,375
[water splashing]

282
00:13:20,458 --> 00:13:22,125
HIROKO:<i> How 'bout that?</i>

283
00:13:22,208 --> 00:13:24,250
<i>Maybe Kousei's not</i>
<i>all grown up yet.</i>

284
00:13:24,333 --> 00:13:26,208
[insects buzzing]

285
00:13:26,291 --> 00:13:28,375
- Here you go, Ms.--

286
00:13:28,458 --> 00:13:31,000
uh, Hiroko.
You take it black, right?

287
00:13:31,083 --> 00:13:33,458
- At least you remember
the important stuff.

288
00:13:33,541 --> 00:13:35,375
Hey, when's your dad
get back in town?

289
00:13:35,458 --> 00:13:36,458
- Don't know.

290
00:13:36,541 --> 00:13:38,041
- Yeah, that's about par
for the course.

291
00:13:38,125 --> 00:13:40,458
- I've got some cold milk
if you'd like a glass.

292
00:13:40,541 --> 00:13:42,208
- [whimpers]
- [chuckles]

293
00:13:42,291 --> 00:13:43,916
She'll come around eventually.

294
00:13:45,625 --> 00:13:46,666
[sips]

295
00:13:48,416 --> 00:13:50,208
Tell you the truth,

296
00:13:50,291 --> 00:13:53,500
I never thought I'd see the day
where you took up piano again.

297
00:13:53,583 --> 00:13:55,041
- You and me both.

298
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:00,958
- So what prompted
this unlikely miracle?

299
00:14:02,250 --> 00:14:04,208
- [chuckles]

300
00:14:04,291 --> 00:14:06,166
[insects buzzing]

301
00:14:12,333 --> 00:14:15,583
- [laughs]

302
00:14:20,083 --> 00:14:22,666
- Summer vacation
is almost here.

303
00:14:22,750 --> 00:14:23,416
-<i> Achtung!</i>
There will be no breaks

304
00:14:23,500 --> 00:14:25,833
for us,<i> Herr</i> Friend A.

305
00:14:25,916 --> 00:14:27,208
- Uh...

306
00:14:27,291 --> 00:14:28,416
- Check it out,

307
00:14:28,500 --> 00:14:30,250
an invite from Towa Hall.

308
00:14:30,333 --> 00:14:31,791
I got it a few days ago.

309
00:14:31,875 --> 00:14:33,333
- What kind of invite?

310
00:14:33,416 --> 00:14:35,250
- Hey, that's the place

311
00:14:35,333 --> 00:14:37,666
where Kousei backed you up
on the piano.

312
00:14:37,750 --> 00:14:41,625
- This wouldn't have to
do
with their big gala
concert?

313
00:14:41,708 --> 00:14:43,291
- Righto!

314
00:14:43,375 --> 00:14:45,375
As I'm sure you know,

315
00:14:45,458 --> 00:14:47,458
they hold concerts like this
every now and then

316
00:14:47,541 --> 00:14:49,083
to commemorate something cool.

317
00:14:49,166 --> 00:14:51,166
This time around,
they're having the recital

318
00:14:51,250 --> 00:14:53,125
to honor the high level
of musicianship

319
00:14:53,208 --> 00:14:55,291
displayed by the winners
and other top performers

320
00:14:55,375 --> 00:14:57,250
at the Towa Music Competition.

321
00:14:57,333 --> 00:14:58,291
- Gotcha.
- Huh?

322
00:14:58,375 --> 00:15:00,041
So if music were like sports,

323
00:15:00,125 --> 00:15:00,791
this would be
an exhibition match?

324
00:15:00,875 --> 00:15:02,083
- A-plus, you!
- [gasps]

325
00:15:03,916 --> 00:15:05,291
- Guess we did something right,

326
00:15:05,375 --> 00:15:08,208
because the promoters really
want us to play their event.

327
00:15:08,666 --> 00:15:09,625
That's me...

328
00:15:09,708 --> 00:15:12,333
- and you.
- [gasps]

329
00:15:12,416 --> 00:15:15,416
- Awesome! Looks like we're
getting the band back
together!

330
00:15:16,625 --> 00:15:18,291
- I'm not gonna force you,
though.

331
00:15:19,541 --> 00:15:22,666
[audience cheering]

332
00:15:26,583 --> 00:15:28,083
It's your call.

333
00:15:28,166 --> 00:15:30,041
[wind blowing]

334
00:15:32,583 --> 00:15:34,166
[student chatter]

335
00:15:34,250 --> 00:15:35,583
KOUSEI: Did you have
a particular song

336
00:15:35,666 --> 00:15:37,041
in mind for the concert?

337
00:15:37,125 --> 00:15:39,458
- Yep. Here. This one.

338
00:15:39,541 --> 00:15:41,041
- Hmm?
- [metal bat rings]

339
00:15:41,125 --> 00:15:41,666
But this is...

340
00:15:41,750 --> 00:15:43,958
- Friedrich Kreisler.

341
00:15:44,041 --> 00:15:45,666
It's his "Liebesleid."

342
00:15:46,416 --> 00:15:48,875
-<i> Meaning "Love's Sorrow."</i>

343
00:15:48,958 --> 00:15:50,958
SAKI:<i> Kousei.</i>

344
00:15:51,041 --> 00:15:53,166
- And you're sure
you wanna play this?

345
00:15:53,250 --> 00:15:56,208
These galas are usually a place
for people to show off,

346
00:15:56,291 --> 00:15:57,000
and this one's really quiet.

347
00:15:57,083 --> 00:15:59,375
- Shows what you know, mister.

348
00:15:59,458 --> 00:16:01,416
I've given this matter
a ton of thought.

349
00:16:01,500 --> 00:16:03,166
If everybody else is going big,

350
00:16:03,250 --> 00:16:05,291
us taking the chill route
will make a splash.

351
00:16:05,375 --> 00:16:08,083
Come on. I didn't roll in
off the turnip truck.

352
00:16:13,250 --> 00:16:15,250
- Let's pick another,

353
00:16:15,333 --> 00:16:17,166
something cooler maybe.

354
00:16:33,041 --> 00:16:33,458
- I'm so sorry.

355
00:16:33,541 --> 00:16:35,666
- [gasps]

356
00:16:35,750 --> 00:16:38,291
- I never meant
to drop you like that,

357
00:16:38,375 --> 00:16:40,708
and words don't
make up for it.

358
00:16:40,791 --> 00:16:42,166
Forgive me.

359
00:16:42,916 --> 00:16:45,416
Just grant me a little more
of your magic.

360
00:16:48,083 --> 00:16:50,291
-<i> She looks so delicate,</i>

361
00:16:50,375 --> 00:16:52,166
<i>like she'd crumble to dust</i>
<i>if I touched her.</i>

362
00:16:56,375 --> 00:16:58,125
- All right.

363
00:16:59,333 --> 00:17:00,583
Let's do it.

364
00:17:00,666 --> 00:17:01,750
- [chuckles]

365
00:17:03,041 --> 00:17:05,875
<i>- So what prompted</i>
<i>this unlikely miracle?</i>

366
00:17:05,958 --> 00:17:06,583
- [sipping]

367
00:17:06,666 --> 00:17:09,458
- This one day in April,

368
00:17:09,541 --> 00:17:12,416
I met a violinist
as crazy as they come,

369
00:17:12,500 --> 00:17:14,333
a total loose cannon,

370
00:17:14,416 --> 00:17:16,083
and what a temper.

371
00:17:16,166 --> 00:17:17,958
But when she smiles at you,

372
00:17:18,041 --> 00:17:19,916
it's like she's an angel.

373
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:22,250
She punched and kicked

374
00:17:22,333 --> 00:17:23,791
and cajoled me onto that stage.

375
00:17:23,875 --> 00:17:26,958
And once I was finally there,

376
00:17:27,041 --> 00:17:30,083
I saw something
that touched my soul.

377
00:17:30,166 --> 00:17:34,125
I just--I know I want to see it
again, no matter what.

378
00:17:34,208 --> 00:17:35,708
And since that's the goal,

379
00:17:35,791 --> 00:17:40,041
I thought maybe I should
become a crazy pianist, right?

380
00:17:40,125 --> 00:17:41,416
- [gasps]

381
00:17:41,500 --> 00:17:42,291
Maybe.

382
00:17:42,375 --> 00:17:45,208
- [grunting]
- Crazy! Crazy! Crazy!

383
00:17:45,291 --> 00:17:46,416
- Okay, then.
- Crazy! Crazy!

384
00:17:46,500 --> 00:17:48,125
- I'm gonna teach you
how to play.

385
00:17:48,208 --> 00:17:49,166
- Huh?

386
00:17:49,250 --> 00:17:51,041
- You don't gotta look
so scared about it.

387
00:17:51,125 --> 00:17:52,791
- Sorry.

388
00:17:52,875 --> 00:17:54,083
- [chuckles]

389
00:18:10,916 --> 00:18:15,041
- Hiroko, I would be honored
to have you teach me.

390
00:18:15,125 --> 00:18:16,250
[footsteps pattering]

391
00:18:19,708 --> 00:18:21,708
- Look, slacker,
you gotta take this seriously.

392
00:18:21,791 --> 00:18:24,166
- Who says that I'm not?

393
00:18:24,250 --> 00:18:26,166
That was our first time
running the piece.

394
00:18:26,250 --> 00:18:26,750
It's gonna get better.

395
00:18:26,833 --> 00:18:29,458
- No excuses. Eh?

396
00:18:29,541 --> 00:18:30,333
[laughing]

397
00:18:30,416 --> 00:18:32,125
- Huh?!

398
00:18:33,375 --> 00:18:34,750
- Just look at 'em!

399
00:18:35,791 --> 00:18:38,083
Oh, wow.

400
00:18:41,708 --> 00:18:43,458
Aren't they beautiful?

401
00:18:46,750 --> 00:18:48,875
- Gotcha!
- Easy, now.

402
00:18:48,958 --> 00:18:49,291
- [sighs]

403
00:18:51,375 --> 00:18:53,708
It's so fragile and weak,

404
00:18:53,791 --> 00:18:57,083
but look how bright it shines.

405
00:18:57,625 --> 00:18:58,666
Thump, thump,

406
00:18:58,750 --> 00:19:01,166
like a heartbeat.

407
00:19:02,458 --> 00:19:03,958
["My Truth" playing]

408
00:19:04,041 --> 00:19:06,208
This light is made
of life itself.

409
00:19:12,625 --> 00:19:13,708
[clears throat]

410
00:19:13,791 --> 00:19:14,500
Is this on?

411
00:19:14,583 --> 00:19:17,041
- Eh?

412
00:19:17,125 --> 00:19:19,625
- So, Friend A, how did
that competition treat you?

413
00:19:19,708 --> 00:19:22,791
[giggles]

414
00:19:22,875 --> 00:19:24,125
- [singing in Japanese]

415
00:19:26,458 --> 00:19:30,000
- You know, I learned something
up on that stage.

416
00:19:30,083 --> 00:19:31,083
Everyone has something
in their heart

417
00:19:31,166 --> 00:19:34,750
that lets them
give the song their all.

418
00:19:34,833 --> 00:19:37,291
For some, it takes
the form of anger.

419
00:19:37,375 --> 00:19:40,625
Sometimes it's hope
or the need to be seen.

420
00:19:40,708 --> 00:19:43,583
The thought let it reach them...

421
00:19:43,666 --> 00:19:45,541
thoughts of a parent.

422
00:19:45,625 --> 00:19:48,250
All of us brought a different
reason onto that stage.

423
00:19:50,166 --> 00:19:52,083
Maybe you have to.

424
00:19:52,166 --> 00:19:54,250
Maybe going out there
empty-handed just doesn't work.

425
00:19:56,166 --> 00:19:57,083
- And you?

426
00:19:57,166 --> 00:19:58,500
- [gasps]

427
00:19:58,583 --> 00:20:00,791
- What did you have
in your heart up there?

428
00:20:00,875 --> 00:20:03,500
What was your inspiration?

429
00:20:03,916 --> 00:20:05,750
- [gasps]

430
00:20:20,875 --> 00:20:22,333
I had you.

431
00:20:24,833 --> 00:20:26,875
- [singing in Japanese]

432
00:20:37,875 --> 00:20:41,750
KOUSEI:<i> My journey, it's begun</i>

433
00:20:41,833 --> 00:20:44,166
<i>to the roar of applause.</i>

434
00:20:44,250 --> 00:20:48,291
<i>I pursue that magical moment</i>
<i>when my music reached them</i>

435
00:20:48,375 --> 00:20:51,625
<i>and the magical soul</i>
<i>who leads me.</i>

436
00:20:52,333 --> 00:20:55,458
<i>I know that someday</i>

437
00:20:55,541 --> 00:21:00,125
<i>I'll walk alongside her</i>
<i>step for step.</i>

438
00:21:02,708 --> 00:21:03,291
Let's call it a night.

439
00:21:03,375 --> 00:21:05,708
- [singing in Japanese]

440
00:21:12,416 --> 00:21:13,833
- "You know...

441
00:21:15,208 --> 00:21:17,666
I'm not always going to be
around to help you."

442
00:21:18,791 --> 00:21:20,791
Charlie Brown.

443
00:21:20,875 --> 00:21:24,750
["Kirameki" playing]

444
